    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our offensive production hinges on exploiting favorable matchups against middling starters. **Jose Caballero** (77.16) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) represent our premier starts. **Jose Caballero** remains a prioritized asset due to the scarcity of stolen bases in our 5x5 format; his efficiency score is boosted by an advantageous matchup against Springs and the specific tactical edge of an 86% stolen base success rate against the starter\u2019s slow delivery. Similarly, **Mickey Moniak** is positioned for a high-output day, leveraging his strong platoon split against the right-handed Randy V\u00e1squez. While **Giancarlo Stanton** (67.71) and **Max Muncy** (61.96) offer solid floor security and power potential, our focus remains on the aggressive base-running profiles like **Jose Caballero** to differentiate in the SB category.\n\nThe bench decision matrix was narrow, with **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** serving as the most notable exclusion. Despite a high underlying projection, his absence from the official starting lineup rendered him a non-factor for today\u2019s points. Conversely, **Vinnie Pasquantino** (51.61), **Zach McKinstry** (49.64), **Kyle Karros** (48.59), and **Tyler Soderstrom** (52.89) all hovered in the marginal range. We are proceeding with these starters to manage our game caps effectively, though **Kyle Karros** remains a risk-heavy play pending final lineup confirmation; if his position drops further down the order, his utility diminishes rapidly. We are navigating a day where park factors and SP skill metrics provide modest lifts for **Max Muncy** and **Giancarlo Stanton**, but we remain vigilant regarding the potential for mid-game substitutions if weather or early blowouts disrupt the expected pace of play.",
